///|
/// File system event generated by `@fs.Watcher`.
///
/// - `Create(path)`: a new file is created at `path`
///
/// - `Remove(path)`: the file at `path` is removed
///
/// - `Rename(old~, new~)`: the file at `old` is moved to location `new`.
///    Note that only rename operation within the watched tree will be reported as `Rename`.
///    Moving a file out of the watched tree will result in a `Remove` event,
///    while moving a file into the watched tree will result in a `Create` event.
///
///    Note that rename detection is inherently racy due to OS limitations,
///    and is only best-effort. Although rare, it is still possible for a rename operation
///    to appear as separated `Remove` + `Create` operations.
///
/// - `Modify(path)`: the file at `path` is modified
///
/// - `Overflow`: too many file system events are generated and cannot be processed.
///    the user should assume all content in the watched directory may have changed
///    upon receiving this event.
///
///    The watcher will still automatically rescan the directory,
///    and ensure that at least `Create`/`Remove`/`Rename` events are properly reported,
///    in a way that can rebuild the current state of the watched directory.
///
/// Here are some special cases:
///
/// - if a rename operation replaces an existing file,
///   a `Remove` event will be reported on that location first,
///   before the actual event for the rename operation itself
///
/// - When a directory is moved into/out of the watched tree,
///   no event will be generated for files inside that directory.
///   Similarly for rename operations.
///
/// - when modifying a file with multiple hard links within the watched tree,
///   the behavior is currently undefined. It is only guaranteed that a `Modify` event
///   will be generated on at least one of the hard liks.
pub(all) enum FsEvent {
  Create(String)
  Remove(String)
  Rename(old~ : String, new~ : String)
  Modify(String)
  Overflow
} derive(Eq, Hash, Debug)
